# MEMORY.md — Index

Long-term memory is split into focused files for better recall. This file is the map.

## Fast-Start Memory

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `memory/session-brief.md` | What matters right now. Read first. |
| `memory/subagent-ledger.md` | Active, stale, or recently completed subagent work. |
| `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` | Daily raw logs for recency and handoff context. |

## Durable Memory

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `memory/projects.md` | Active projects, milestones, blockers |
| `memory/people.md` | Relationship context and communication notes |
| `memory/preferences.md` | {{NAME}}'s preferences and recurring patterns |
| `memory/operating-rules.md` | Cross-session lessons and behavior corrections |
| `memory/rules-constitutional.md` | Hard rules that should rarely change |
| `memory/rules-tactical.md` | Evolving conventions and local playbooks |
| `memory/context-holds.md` | Temporary focus shifts with expiry |
| `memory/predictions.md` | Prediction-outcome calibration |
| `memory/regressions.md` | Failure-to-guardrail pipeline |
| `memory/reference/conventions.md` | Type tags, trust scoring, memory conventions |

## How to Use This

1. Start with `memory/session-brief.md`.
2. Read today + yesterday from `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`.
3. Use the durable files when you need stable context or rules.
4. Keep the semantic layer optional. Plain-text files remain the source of truth.

